	THE COPY STATEMENT PREFIX PATH (-P OPTION)
	==========================================

	This document describes the prefix path (-P) option of the WISP
	translator.  This option is currently available for UNIX and MSDOS
	only.

	This options changes the way the WISP translator processes COPY 
	statements which include the "IN library" clause.  If the "IN library"
	clause is not used with a COPY statement then this option has no
	effect and that COPY statement is processed in the normal manner.

	The prefix path (-P) option allows you to specify a path which is
	to be searched for the copy library/file combination.  The normal
	behavior of WISP without the prefix path option would be to look
	only for "../library/file.wcb".  This is different then the inlib
	(-I) option which is only used when the "IN library" clause is
	not specified.

	Usage:
		$ wisp -P prefixpath file

		Prefixpath is a list of one or more directories separated
		by colons (:) for UNIX and semicolons (;) for MSDOS.

	Example:

		$ wisp -P/home/me/testlib:/disk1/qalib:/disk1/mastlib sample

		If SAMPLE contains a copy statement of the form:

		COPY FDPAYNOW IN ACCTCOPY.

		WISP will look in sequence until it finds one of the 
		following:

		/home/me/testlib/acctcopy/fdpaynow.wcb
		/disk1/qalib/acctcopy/fdpaynow.wcb
		/disk1/mastlib/acctcopy/fdpaynow.wcb


	Using Prefix Path In Convert Mode
	---------------------------------

	When used in CONVERT mode WISP will generate the following COPY
	statement for the example above:

		COPY "acctcopy/fdpaynow.wcb"

	To compile the COBOL after translating in CONVERT mode it will be
	necessary to inform the compiler about the prefix path.  The following
	examples show how to do this for MicroFocus COBOL and AcuCOBOL on
	UNIX.

	MicroFocus:	
		$ COBCPY="/home/me/testlib:/disk1/qalib:/disk1/mastlib"
		$ export COBCPY

	AcuCOBOL:
		$ COPYPATH="/home/me/testlib:/disk1/qalib:/disk1/mastlib"
		$ export COPYPATH

